title: Beef Tenderloin with Parsnip Slaw and Thai Peanut Sauce
summary: Beef Tenderloin with Parsnip Slaw and Thai Peanut Sauce might be just the main course you are searching for. This recipe serves 4 and costs $8.97 per serving. Watching your figure? This gluten free and dairy free recipe has 1601 calories, 61g of protein, and 120g of fat per serving. This recipe is liked by 2 foodies and cooks. Only a few people really liked this Asian dish. From preparation to the plate, this recipe takes around 40 minutes. It will be a hit at your The Fourth Of July event. It is brought to you by Foodnetwork. Head to the store and pick up agave nectar, soy sauce, napa cabbage, and a few other things to make it today. To use up the agave nectar you could follow this main course with the Chocolate Brownie Batter Blizzard as a dessert. With a spoonacular score of 86%, this dish is amazing. Try Beef Tenderloin with Parsnip Slaw and Thai Peanut Sauce, Extra Sticky Thai BBQ Ribs w/Peanut BBQ Sauce + Sweet Thai Ginger Slaw, and Thai Tacos with Ginger Slaw and Peanut Sauce for similar recipes.

winePairing.pairingText: Riesling, Gewurztraminer, and Chenin Blanc are my top picks for Asian. The best wine for Asian food depends on the cuisine and dish - of course - but these acidic whites pair with a number of traditional meals, spicy or not. You could try Fritz Haag Brauneberger Juffer Spatlese Riesling. Reviewers quite like it with a 4.4 out of 5 star rating and a price of about 30 dollars per bottle.

productMatches.title: Fritz Haag Brauneberger Juffer Spatlese Riesling
productMatches.description: The late-picked Brauneberger Juffer Riesling Spatlese has fine, forceful fruit in the aroma, a linear focus on the palate and a pure slate finish. This wine is a great choice for spicy dishes with fresh flavors and a lively sweet/tart balance.

instructions: Preheat the oven to 400 degrees F.                          In a large bowl, whisk together the mayonnaise, peanut butter, sugar, and vinegar. Add in the cabbage, parsnips, carrots, cilantro, onion, and garlic. Toss to coat with the dressing.                          Heat a large oven-proof saute pan over medium-high heat and add the olive oil. Season the beef tenderloin with salt, and pepper, and sear on all sides until brown. Transfer the pan to the oven and cook the tenderloin for about 20 to 30 minutes, or until medium-rare and internal temperature is 145 degrees F. Remove the beef from the pan. Place the pan back on medium heat and de-glaze with the soy sauce. Stir the sauce to scrape up the brown bits from the bottom of the pan. Remove the pan from the heat. Thinly slice the tenderloin and lay on a bed of parsnip slaw. Serve with a side of Thai Peanut Sauce.                          In a blender or food processor, mix the peanut butter, coconut milk, agave nectar, lime juice, soy sauce, garlic powder, to taste, and red pepper flakes, to taste together until the texture is smooth and loose.

steps.step: Preheat the oven to 400 degrees F.
In a large bowl, whisk together the mayonnaise, peanut butter, sugar, and vinegar.
Add in the cabbage, parsnips, carrots, cilantro, onion, and garlic. Toss to coat with the dressing.
Heat a large oven-proof saute pan over medium-high heat and add the olive oil. Season the beef tenderloin with salt, and pepper, and sear on all sides until brown.
Transfer the pan to the oven and cook the tenderloin for about 20 to 30 minutes, or until medium-rare and internal temperature is 145 degrees F.
Remove the beef from the pan.
Place the pan back on medium heat and de-glaze with the soy sauce. Stir the sauce to scrape up the brown bits from the bottom of the pan.
Remove the pan from the heat. Thinly slice the tenderloin and lay on a bed of parsnip slaw.
Serve with a side of Thai Peanut Sauce.

In a blender or food processor, mix the peanut butter, coconut milk, agave nectar, lime juice, soy sauce, garlic powder, to taste, and red pepper flakes, to taste together until the texture is smooth and loose.
